{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015mF2Mfr2x5CJFFWCY2t8E8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the Flask nested blueprint URL prefix resolution. Let me analyze the key sections:\n\n1. **`BlueprintSetupState.__init__`** (lines 72-77): \n   - Gets `url_prefix` from options first, then falls back to `blueprint.url_prefix`\n   - This becomes `state.url_prefix`\n\n2. **`BlueprintSetupState.add_url_rule`** (lines 87-116):\n   - Applies `self.url_prefix` to each rule\n\n3. **`Blueprint.register`** (lines 349-377): The nested blueprint registration logic:\n   - When registering nested blueprints, it iterates through each one and checks if a `url_prefix` was explicitly passed in the options\n   - If no prefix was provided in the options, it falls back to the blueprint's own `url_prefix` attribute\n   - Then it combines the parent's `state.url_prefix` with the nested blueprint's prefix by concatenating them together\n\n, handling the slashes properly\n   - If only one of them exists, it uses that one\n\nNow I'm checking the Flask version to see if this logic might be different in an older version where the bug was reported. I'm checking an older version of the code to see if this was a previous issue. Looking at the current 3.1.0 implementation, the `url_prefix` gets pulled from the options passed to `register_blueprint()` first, then falls back to what's set directly on the blueprint itself. Since the user didn't pass `url_prefix` as an option, it should use the `/users` prefix from the blueprint, which combined with the `/api` state prefix should give the correct route path.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8863,"cache_read_input_tokens":19738,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8863},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_g