fix passed to the child blueprint's `register()` call becomes just `/api` — the child's own `/users` prefix is silently dropped.\",\n    \"Step 6 (bug): `users_bp.register(app, bp_options)` is called with `bp_options['url_prefix'] = '/api'`. Inside `BlueprintSetupState.__init__`, `state.url_prefix = '/api'`. When `add_url_rule` fires for each route, rules are prefixed with `/api` only — routes land at `/api/<route>` instead of `/api/users/<route>`.\",\n    \"Step 7 (fix in 2.0.1): Lines 364–365 were added: `if bp_url_prefix is None: bp_url_prefix = blueprint.url_prefix`. Now `bp_url_prefix = '/users'`. The combination branch (lines 367–370) fires: `bp_options['url_prefix'] = '/api' + '/' + 'users' = '/api/users'`, and routes correctly land at `/api/users/<route>`.\"\n  ],\n  \"trigger_conditions\": [\n    \"The nested blueprint is created with `url_prefix` set in its constructor (e.g., `Blueprint('users', __name__, url_prefix='/users')`).\",\n    \"`url_prefix` is NOT passed as a keyword argument to `parent_bp.register_blueprint(child_bp)` — i.e., bp_options dict is empty or lacks 'url_prefix'.\",\n    \"The parent blueprint (or the options it was registered with) has a non-None `url_prefix` (i.e., `state.url_prefix is not None`).\",\n    \"Flask version < 2.0.1 (the fix was introduced in 2.0.1, :issue:`4037`). In 2.0.0 the fallback `bp_url_prefix = blueprint.url_prefix` was missing from the nested-blueprint loop in `Blueprint.register()`.\"\n  ],\n  \"code_paths\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py\",\n      \"description\": \"Blueprint.register_blueprint() — stores (child_bp, options) in self._blueprints (line 271). No URL resolution happens here.\",\n      \"lines\": \"256-271\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py\",\n      \"description\": \"Blueprint.register() — iterates self._blueprints and builds the combined url_prefix for each nested blueprint before calling child.register(). Lines 349-377 are the core nested-blueprint prefix combination logic. Lines 364-365 (if bp_url_prefix is None: bp_url_prefix = blueprint.url_prefix) are the fix added in 2.0.1.\",\n      \"lines\": \"273-377\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py\",\n      \"description\": \"BlueprintSetupState.__init__() — resolves url_prefix from options dict first, then falls back to blueprint.url_prefix (lines 72-77). Sets self.url_prefix used by add_url_rule.\",\n      \"lines\": \"41-85\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py\",\n      \"description\": \"BlueprintSetupState.add_url_rule() — applies self.url_prefix to every registered route rule (lines 98-102). This is where the wrong/missing prefix is stamped onto final route paths.\",\n      \"lines\": \"87-116\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ownership\": \"Blueprint URL registration subsystem — specifically the nested blueprint registration loop inside Blueprint.register() in src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py. This was introduced in Flask 2.0 (Scaffold refactor, :pr:`3215`) and the url_prefix combination bug was fixed in 2.0.1 (:issue:`4037`).\",\n  \"severity\": {\n    \"level\": \"medium\",\n    \"rationale\": \"Silently produces wrong URL routing (routes unreachable at expected paths) when nesting blueprints that declare url_prefix at construction time, which is a common and recommended pattern. There is no error or warning — the app starts normally but routes land at incorrect paths, causing 404s. Workaround exists: pass url_prefix explicitly to register_blueprint() instead of declaring it on the child blueprint constructor. Fixed in Flask 2.0.1.\"\n  }\n}\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PagfMrWUq36RzCnoMJDV8C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here's a summary of the findings:\n\n## Nested Blueprint `url_prefix` Ignored — Root Cause\n\n**File:** `src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py`\n\n### How `register_blueprint` propagates nested prefixes\n\n1. **`Blueprint.register_blueprint()`** (line 271) merely appends `(child_bp, options)` to `self._blueprints`. No URL logic runs here.\n\n2. **`Blueprint.register()`** (lines 349–377) is where prefix combination actually happens. When the parent blueprint is registered with the app, it loops over `self._blueprints` and builds a combined `url_prefix` for each child before calling `child.register(app, bp_options)`.\n\n3. **`BlueprintSetupState.__init__`** (lines 72–77) resolves `url_prefix` from options, then falls back to `blueprint.url_prefix`. This sets `state.url_prefix` used by every `add_url_rule()` call.\n\n### Where the prefix gets dropped\n\nThe bug (Flask 2.0.0, fixed in 2.0.1 via `:issue:4037`) was in `Blueprint.register()`:\n\n```python\nbp_url_prefix = bp_options.get(\"url_prefix\")  # None — not passed to register_blueprint()\n# BUG: missing fallback:\n# if bp_url_prefix is None:\n#     bp_url_prefix = blueprint.url_prefix     ← THIS LINE WAS ABSENT in 2.0.0\n```\n\nWithout the fallback, `bp_url_prefix` stays `None`, the combination condition `state.url_prefix is not None and bp_url_prefix is not None` is False, and execution falls through to `elif state.url_prefix is not None: bp_options[\"url_prefix\"] = state.url_prefix` — giving the child just `/api` instead of `/api/users`.\n\n### Trigger conditions\n1. Child blueprint created with `url_prefix=` in its constructor  \n2. `url_prefix` **not** passed as keyword arg to `parent.register_blueprint(child)`  \n3. Parent has a non-`None` url_prefix  \n4. Flask version < 2.0.1"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_